Male genitalia
(
paratype
) (Genital preparation Ñ OG–004-2016) (
Figs 22–25
). Tegumen-uncus complex relatively broad; scopula androconialis well-developed, about twice as short as tegumen-uncus complex (
Fig. 22
); crista gnathi medialis long and broad; crista gnati lateralis subcardiform, about twice as short and narrower than crista gnathi medialis (
Fig. 22
); valva (
Fig. 23
) trapeziform-ovoid, crista sacculi straight, broad, covered with apically pointed setae cranially and flat-topped ones caudally; caudal part of setae bent towards ventral margin; saccus (
Fig. 24
) broad, rounded basally, long, about twice longer than vinculum; aedeagus (
Fig. 24
) thin, straight, slightly shorter than valva; vesica with numerous small cornuti.

Female genitalia
(
paratype
) (Genital preparation Ñ OG–003-2016) (
Fig. 21
). Papillae anales relatively broad, covered with short and long setae; 8th tergite broad with short setae at ventro-caudal margin, triangular with folded inside ventral margin; posterior apophysis slightly longer than anterior apophysis; both lamellae antevaginalis and postvaginalis undeveloped; ostium bursae tube-shaped, situated at ventro-anterior edge of 8th tergite; antrum relatively narrow, long, about twice shorted than posterior apophysis, well-sclerotized in posterior half; ductus bursae membranous, slightly broader than antrum, with numerous wrinkles medially; relatively long, about as long as antrum; corpus bursae gradually widening from base, without signum.

The flight period is rather short and continues for about a week in mid July, probably depending on weather conditions. Males are active from late morning; females were captured in early afternoon flying near the host plant or resting on it (
Fig. 30
).
